Testing Residual Timing Effects After State Stabilisation

A timing-resolved test of history-dependent behaviour in sequential quantum preparation

Author: Mina Moussa
Date: 2026-05-03


---

Overview

This proposal tests whether prior state-transition history can leave a measurable timing signature even after a system is prepared into a stable, repeated state.

Standard quantum mechanics predicts:

> Once a system is prepared into a given state, all future observables depend only on that state, not on how it was reached.



This work challenges whether this holds for timing observables at high precision.


---

Core Question

> Does a system that has undergone many prior state transitions exhibit identical timing behaviour to a system prepared directly into the same final state?



Specifically:

> After a period of alternating state changes, does a subsequent repeated same-state phase show any residual timing deviation?




---

Experimental Concept

Two preparation conditions are constructed:

Condition A — Direct Stabilisation

U → U → U → U → U → U → U → U

Condition B — Alternating History + Stabilisation

U → D → U → D → U → D → U → D → U → U → U → U → U

Only the final repeated Up phase is measured:

U → U → U → U → U


---

Measurement Strategy

Measurements are performed only on the final repeated-state phase, excluding the switching region.

Primary observable:

Mean arrival time

Timing variance

Distribution shape (tails, skewness)



---

Standard Quantum Prediction

If the system is fully described by its current state:

ΔT_final = 0
ΔVar_final = 0

within experimental uncertainty.

That is:

> The timing distribution of the final repeated Up phase is independent of prior history.




---

Alternative Hypothesis

If prior transitions leave residual structure:

> The final repeated-state phase may exhibit a transient timing deviation.



This can be modelled as:

delay(k) = A × exp(-k / τ)

Where:

k = index within repeated-state phase

A = initial residual timing offset

τ = relaxation timescale


Predicted effects:

Initial delay in first few repeated-state events

Gradual convergence to baseline timing

Possible increased variance or asymmetric distribution



---

Key Principle

The experiment explicitly separates:

Known system-induced delay (during switching)

Residual delay after switching has stopped


Only the latter is tested.


---

Critical Controls

To isolate the effect:

System Controls

Stable interferometer path length

Detector timing calibration

Laser pulse stability


Logical Controls

Swap U/D encoding

Reverse sequence ordering

Randomised sequences


Reset Control

Full system reset between runs



---

Residual Extraction

Measured timing:

ΔT_measured = ΔT_system + ΔT_history + noise

Subtract known system contribution:

ΔT_residual = ΔT_measured - ΔT_system

Test whether:

ΔT_residual ≠ 0

and follows decay structure.


---

Sensitivity and Scale

Given:

Detector jitter ≈ 10–20 ps

Target timing sensitivity ≈ 0.001–0.01 ps


Detection requires:

N ≈ (jitter / ΔT)^2

Example:

ΔT ≈ 0.002 ps

jitter ≈ 18 ps


N ≈ 10^9 measurements


---

Feasibility Insight

This implies:

The effect, if present, is far below single-event resolution

Detection relies on statistical averaging over large datasets

Timing must be measured at sub-picosecond effective precision



---

Interpretation

Null Result

No detectable residual timing:

> Supports standard quantum mechanics
Confirms no history-dependent timing effect




---

Positive Result

Residual timing detected:

Appears only after alternating history

Persists into repeated-state phase

Decays over time


Implication:

> Indicates a history-dependent contribution not captured by standard state description




---

Significance

This experiment targets a minimally explored regime:

Timing as a primary observable

Post-stabilisation behaviour

High-statistics detection of small effects


It does not assume new physics, but tests whether:

> Extremely small history-dependent timing effects exist below current detection limits.




---

Summary

> This work proposes a timing-resolved test of whether prior state-transition history leaves a measurable residual signature after a system enters a stable repeated state. By isolating the post-transition phase and measuring timing at high precision, the experiment probes whether standard state-based descriptions fully capture system behaviour.




---

Plain English Summary

We take two systems that end up in the same state:

One got there directly

One got there after lots of flipping


Then we ask:

> Do they behave the same once they’re stable?



Quantum mechanics says yes.

This experiment checks:

> Have we measured timing precisely enough to be sure?

