Prior Experimental Coverage and Measurement Gap

Extensive experimental work in quantum mechanics has already tested:

Large numbers of particles (photons, electrons, atoms)

Repeated state preparation and measurement

High-precision probability and phase observables


Typical regimes include:

Particle counts:
 to  events in interferometry and photon-counting experiments

Repeated state preparation cycles:
Thousands to millions of sequential operations in quantum optics and quantum information systems

Measurement focus:

Output probabilities

Interference visibility

Phase coherence




---

Critical Observation

Despite this extensive coverage:

> Timing behaviour in a stabilised repeated-state phase following a transition-heavy preparation sequence has not been systematically probed at sub-picosecond precision.



In particular, prior experiments typically:

Measure during or immediately after state preparation

Focus on probability distributions rather than timing distributions

Do not isolate the post-transition stabilisation phase as a separate observable



---

Unexplored Regime

This proposal targets the following regime:

High transition depth:
 to  state transitions prior to stabilisation

Stabilised repeated-state phase:
Measurement performed only after transitions cease

High-statistics measurement:
 to  events required for resolving sub-picosecond effects

Timing sensitivity:
 to  ps (femtosecond scale, achieved via averaging)



---

Why Prior Null Results Do Not Exclude This Effect

Existing null results operate within regimes where:

Timing precision is limited to picosecond scale or coarser

Observables are dominated by probability and phase measurements

Transition and stabilised phases are not explicitly separated


Therefore:

> A residual timing effect that is both extremely small (femtosecond scale) and present only after stabilisation may remain undetected within current experimental approaches.




---

Guidance for Experimental Testing

To meaningfully test this hypothesis, experiments should:

Use sufficiently large datasets (≥ – events)

Apply transition-heavy preparation sequences before stabilisation

Measure only the post-transition repeated-state phase

Use statistical averaging to reach sub-picosecond effective timing resolution

Explicitly separate known system-induced delays from residual timing behaviour



---

Key Message

> A null result obtained with limited particle counts, low transition depth, or insufficient timing precision does not exclude the presence of a history-dependent timing effect at the scales proposed here.




---

Plain English Summary

Physics has tested large numbers of particles and repeated state changes —
but not this specific combination:

many state changes

followed by a stable repeated state

measured with extremely precise timing


This means:

> A very small timing effect could exist and remain undetected, not because it isn’t real, but because it hasn’t been measured in the right regime yet.


